# {{.Name}} — knowledge base schema

This repository is an LLM-maintained wiki ("{{.Name}}"). You — the agent — are
its librarian. Humans read this wiki; you write it. Follow this schema exactly.

## Layers

1. **`raw/` — immutable ground truth.** Source documents (articles, notes,
   exports from external systems). Read them freely. NEVER modify or delete
   anything under `raw/`. The wiki can always be recompiled from raw.
2. **`wiki/` — the compiled knowledge.** Markdown pages you create, update,
   cross-reference, and keep consistent. Entity pages, concept pages,
   comparisons, syntheses. You own this layer entirely.
3. **`llms.txt` + this file — the index and the schema.** Keep `llms.txt`
   current on every ingest: H1 title, one-line blockquote summary, H2 sections
   with `- [Title](path): description` link lists.

## Conventions

- Every wiki page starts with YAML frontmatter: at minimum `title`, `tags`,
  and `sources` (paths of raw documents the page draws from).
- Link between pages with relative markdown links: `[Title](other-page.md)`.
- Cite raw sources by path when making claims.
- Preserve contradictions instead of smoothing them over — flag them
  explicitly in a `## Contradictions` section on the affected page.
- Prefer stable, descriptive page file names (lowercase, hyphenated).
- Keep `wiki/index.md` up to date on every change.
- Append one entry to `wiki/log.md` per operation, newest first, formatted as
  `## [YYYY-MM-DD] operation | Title`.

## Workflows

**Ingest** (new document appears in `raw/`): read it fully, extract key
information, update or create the affected wiki pages, refresh cross-links,
flag contradictions with existing claims, update `wiki/index.md` and
`llms.txt`, log the operation in `wiki/log.md`.

**Answer** (a question about this domain): consult `llms.txt` and
`wiki/index.md` first, follow links to the relevant pages, and only fall back
to `raw/` when the wiki lacks detail. If the wiki was missing something you
had to derive, fold that derivation back into the wiki.

**Maintain**: when you notice stale pages, broken links, or drift between the
wiki and raw sources, fix them and log the maintenance pass.

**Committing**: after any write session, commit with a message summarizing the
operation (e.g. `ingest: 2026-07 product review notes`) and push.
